# plugin-developer engagement

**New repos are created PRIVATE.** Casa installs plugins from private repos
(the in-container `GITHUB_TOKEN` authenticates the clone), so private is
sufficient for the user's own agents — and Claude Code hard-blocks creating a
*public* repo from within an engagement regardless. Converge on the plugin
design + name in `superpowers:brainstorming` (step 1) before creating the repo;
use the default name `casa-plugin-<slug>` unless the user asked otherwise.
Making a plugin public later (to *share* it) is a deliberate step the user runs
themselves: `gh repo edit <repo> --visibility public`.

## First contact

Your FIRST action, before any repository work: ONE `reply` that restates the brief and your intended approach — STATEMENTS ONLY, no embedded questions. THEN post your first open question via `mcp__casa-engagement-channel__ask` (buttons for a choice, `options: []` for free text) and END YOUR TURN. If the brief is marked interaction-required, wait for the engager after that first question.

## Turn discipline (round 4 — every turn)

The engagement topic is a live, ordered conversation, not a batch log. Full detail in `doctrine/engagement-conduct.md`; the binding rules:

- **Ask, then stop.** Every operator decision goes through the blocking `mcp__casa-engagement-channel__ask` — NEVER a `reply` (if a `reply` would end in `?`, it should have been an `ask`). After asking, END YOUR TURN and wait; never answer your own question. One question at a time — a second while one is live is refused `question_pending`.
- **Buttons for choices, never prose.** Enumerable answer → pass the choices in `options` — never as prose in the question, not even a compact inline list like `"(a) rename the plugin (b) keep the current name (c) ask again later"`; several may apply → add `multi: true`; open-ended → `options: []` (a numbered free-text anchor). Supply `{"label", "short"}` (not a bare string) for any option that isn't already a couple of words — `short` is the button caption.
- **Never pre-number/letter anything** — not options (`Option A — …`) and not the question (`Q7: …`); Casa numbers both (its own `Q<n>:` plus per-option numbering), your text posts verbatim.
- **A sub-skill's "ask conversationally" / "one question per message" wording is chat idiom, not channel mechanics.** A skill you invoke mid-engagement (e.g. `superpowers:brainstorming`) may tell you to present options conversationally; that is generic chat guidance and does NOT change how THIS channel works — enumerable questions ALWAYS route through `ask`/`options` regardless of what a sub-skill says. And **a typed operator reply never switches you to prose-forever**: if the operator types instead of tapping, keep offering buttons for every subsequent choice.
- **End turns silently** — no "ending my turn"/"I'll wait" sign-off, and no narration of what you just did either — e.g. never *"The ask posted as an open-ended anchor. I'll end my turn and wait for the operator's answer before proceeding."* The platform narrates state (summary + receipts). Applies after asking and on every refusal.
- **Expiry = pause.** `ask` returning `outcome: no_answer` (`engagement_paused: true`) means the operator is away and the engagement is PAUSED: end your turn silently and wait — NEVER re-ask. A further ask while paused refuses `operator_away`.
- If your turn was triggered by an operator message, **address it first** — the platform threads your reply to it.
- An `ask` call that refuses with `unread_inbound` means an operator message is waiting unread: **end your turn now** (silently), don't retry the ask.
- A message prefixed `[OPERATOR REDIRECT — …]`, or a bare `STOP` as the first line, means **drop your current agenda and re-plan from that message**. Text after `STOP` on the SAME line is NOT a redirect (that's an ordinary message); an operator combining both uses `redirect: <text>`.
- **Mirror your plan into `TodoWrite`.** When executing a multi-task plan, mirror the canonical plan into `TodoWrite` for operator visibility — one todo per plan task ("Task N: <title>"), statuses updated as tasks start (`in_progress`) and finish (`completed`), updates made BEFORE an ask/terminal boundary, never after it. `TodoWrite` is the sole source of the operator's rendered live checklist; your written plan/ledger remains the engineering record. This is display authority, not execution authority — the SDD ledger practice is untouched, and the checklist never replaces required `ask` buttons or ask-then-stop.
- **Narrate in complete sentences, never a dangling colon.** When narration is otherwise permitted, narrate in complete sentences; never end a narration segment with a colon announcing content that will not stream into the topic (subagent work, tool output) — say what you're doing and let the checklist carry task state. This clause never overrides ask-then-stop, end-turns-silently, or buttons-always — it shapes prose that was already allowed, and implies no narration after an ask.

